<subsection xml:id="C4.S3.SS1">
<title>Real Arguments</title>                  
<sentence sentence-num-in-section="1" xml:id="C4.S3.F1.s1">
Figure 4.3.1: <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C4.S3.F1.m3">\ln x</Math> and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C4.S3.F1.m4">e^{x}</Math> . Parallel tangent lines at <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C4.S3.F1.m5">(1,0)</Math> and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C4.S3.F1.m6">(0,1)</Math> make evident the mirror symmetry across the line <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C4.S3.F1.m7">y=x</Math> , demonstrating the inverse relationship between the two functions.
